cs.LG, cs.IR, cs.AI, cs.DS, cs.CE 

This paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it introduces a new practical estimator for evaluating policies based on logged data. It also involves a learning-to-rank task, which is a common problem in machine learning. 

It could also belong to cs.IR (Information Retrieval) as the paper focuses on evaluating policies for recommending an ordered set of items, which is a common scenario in web search and recommendation. 

Additionally, it could be categorized under cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as it involves developing a new estimator for evaluating policies. 

The paper also uses techniques from combinatorial bandits, which could place it under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as this sub-category covers the study of algorithms and data structures for solving computational problems. 

Finally, it could be categorized under cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science) as it involves developing a practical estimator for evaluating policies, which could have applications in various fields such as finance and science.
